# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: agreement-linguistics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] An **adjective** (abbreviated **ADJ**) is a word that describes or defines a noun or noun phrase.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] Its semantic role is to change information given by the noun.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] The adjective is considered one of the main parts of speech of the English language, although historically they were classed together with nouns.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] Nowadays, certain words that usually had been classified as adjectives, including *the*, *this*, *my*, etc., typically are classed separately, as determiners.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] Depending on the language, an adjective can precede a corresponding noun on a prepositive basis or it can follow a corresponding noun on a postpositive basis.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] Structural, contextual, and style considerations can impinge on the pre-or post-position of an adjective in a given instance of its occurrence.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] Adjectives feature as a part of speech (word class) in most languages.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] In some languages, the words that serve the semantic function of adjectives are categorized together with some other class, such as nouns or verbs.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] In the phrase *a Ford car*, *Ford* is unquestionably a noun but its function is adjectival (noun adjunct, see below): to modify *car*.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] In some languages adjectives can function as nouns: for example, the Spanish phrase *un rojo* means 'a red [one]'.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] This is also possible in English, see above.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] As for "confusion" with verbs, rather than an adjective meaning "big", a language might have a verb that means "to be big" and could then use an attributive verb construction analogous to "big-being house" to express what in English is called a "big house".
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] Such an analysis is possible for the grammar of Standard Chinese and Korean, for example.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] Different languages do not use adjectives in exactly the same situations.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] For example, where English uses *"*to be *hungry*" (*hungry* being an adjective), Dutch, French, and Spanish use "*honger hebben*", "*avoir faim*", and "*tener hambre*" respectively (literally "to have hunger", the words for "hunger" being nouns).
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] Similarly, where Hebrew uses the adjective זקוק‎ (*zaqūq*, roughly "in need of" or "needing"), English uses the verb "to need".
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] In languages that have adjectives as a word class, it is usually an open class; that is, it is relatively common for new adjectives to be formed via such processes as derivation.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] However, Bantu languages are well known for having only a small closed class of adjectives, and new adjectives are not easily derived.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] Similarly, native Japanese adjectives (*i*-adjectives) are considered a closed class (as are native verbs), although nouns (an open class) may be used in the genitive to convey some adjectival meanings, and there is also the separate open class of adjectival nouns (*na*-adjectives).
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] Many languages (including English) distinguish between adjectives, which qualify nouns and pronouns, and adverbs, which mainly modify verbs, adjectives, or other adverbs.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] Not all languages make this exact distinction; many (including English) have words that can function as either.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] For example, in English, *fast* is an adjective in "a *fast* car" (where it qualifies the noun *car*) but an adverb in "he drove *fast*" (where it modifies the verb *drove*).
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] A German word like *klug* ("clever(ly)") takes endings when used as an attributive adjective but not when used adverbially.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] Whether these are distinct parts of speech or distinct usages of the same part of speech is a question of analysis.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] While German linguistic terminology distinguishes *adverbiale* from *adjektivische Formen*, German refers to both as *Eigenschaftswörter* ("property words").
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] Linguists today distinguish determiners from adjectives, considering them to be two separate parts of speech (or *lexical categories*).
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] Determiners formerly were considered to be adjectives in some of their uses.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] Determiners function neither as nouns nor pronouns but instead characterize a nominal element within a particular context.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] They generally do this by indicating definiteness (*a* vs.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] An adjective acts as the head of an *adjective phrase* or *adjectival phrase* (AP).
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] In the simplest case, an adjective phrase consists solely of the adjective; more complex adjective phrases may contain one or more adverbs modifying the adjective ("*very* strong"), or one or more complements (such as "worth *several dollars*", "full *of toys*", or "eager *to please*").
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] In English, attributive adjective phrases that include complements typically follow the noun that they qualify ("an evildoer *devoid of redeeming qualities*").
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] In many languages (including English) it is possible for nouns to modify other nouns.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] Unlike adjectives, nouns acting as modifiers (called *attributive nouns* or *noun adjuncts*) usually are not predicative; a beautiful park is beautiful, but a car park is not "car".
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] The modifier often indicates origin ("*Virginia* reel"), purpose ("*work* clothes"), semantic patient ("*man* eater") or semantic subject ("*child* actor"); however, it may generally indicate almost any semantic relationship.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] It is also common for adjectives to be derived from nouns, as in *boyish*, *birdlike*, *behavioral (behavioural)*, *famous*, *manly*, *angelic*, and so on.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] Many languages have participle forms that can act as noun modifiers either alone or as the head of a phrase.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] Sometimes participles develop into functional usage as adjectives.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] Examples in English include *relieved* (the past participle of *relieve*), used as an adjective in passive voice constructs such as "I am so *relieved* to see you".
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] Other examples include *spoken* (the past participle of *speak*) and *going* (the present participle of *go*), which function as attribute adjectives in such phrases as "the *spoken* word" and "the *going* rate".
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] Other constructs that often modify nouns include prepositional phrases (as in "a rebel *without a cause*"), relative clauses (as in "the man *who wasn't there*"), and infinitive phrases (as in "a cake *to die for*").
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] Some nouns can also take complements such as content clauses (as in "the idea *that I would do that*"), but these are not commonly considered modifiers.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] For more information about possible modifiers and dependents of nouns, see Components of noun phrases.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] In Australian Aboriginal languages, the distinction between adjectives and nouns is typically thought weak, and many of the languages only use nouns, or nouns with a limited set of adjective-deriving affixes, to modify other nouns.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] In languages that have a subtle adjective-noun distinction, one way to tell them apart is that a modifying adjective can come to stand in for an entire elided noun phrase, while a modifying noun cannot.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] For example, in Bardi, the adjective *moorrooloo* 'little' in the phrase *moorrooloo* *baawa* 'little child' can stand on its own to mean 'the little one', while the attributive noun *aamba* 'man' in the phrase *aamba baawa* 'male child' cannot stand for the whole phrase to mean 'the male one'.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] In other languages, like Warlpiri, nouns and adjectives are lumped together beneath the nominal umbrella because of their shared syntactic distribution as arguments of predicates.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] The only thing distinguishing them is that some nominals seem to semantically denote entities (typically nouns in English) and some nominals seem to denote attributes (typically adjectives in English).
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] In many languages, attributive adjectives usually occur in a specific order.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] In general, the adjective order in English can be summarised as: opinion, size, age or shape, colour, origin, material, purpose.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] Other language authorities, like the *Cambridge Dictionary*, state that shape precedes rather than follows age.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] Determiners and postdeterminers—articles, numerals, and other limiters (e.g.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] *three* blind mice)—come before attributive adjectives in English.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] Although certain combinations of determiners can appear before a noun, they are far more circumscribed than adjectives in their use—typically, only a single determiner would appear before a noun or noun phrase (including any attributive adjectives).
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] Size – adjectives denoting physical size (e.g.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] Shape or physical quality – adjectives describing more detailed physical attributes than overall size (e.g.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] Colour – adjectives denoting colour or pattern (e.g.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] Origin – denominal adjectives denoting source (e.g.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] This means that, in English, adjectives pertaining to size precede adjectives pertaining to age ("little old", not "old little"), which in turn generally precede adjectives pertaining to colour ("old white", not "white old").
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] This order may be more rigid in some languages than others; in some, like Spanish, it may only be a default (*unmarked*) word order, with other orders being permissible.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] Other languages, such as Tagalog, follow their adjectival orders as rigidly as English.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] The normal adjectival order of English may be overridden in certain circumstances, especially when one adjective is being fronted or with ablaut reduplication.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] For example, the usual order of adjectives in English would result in the phrase "the bad big wolf" (opinion before size), but instead, the usual phrase is "the big bad wolf".
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] Owing partially to borrowings from French, English has some adjectives that follow the noun as postmodifiers, called postpositive adjectives, as in *time immemorial* and *attorney general*.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] Adjectives may even change meaning depending on whether they precede or follow, as in *proper*: "They live in a *proper town*" (a real town, not a village) vs.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] "They live in the *town proper* (in the town itself, not in the suburbs).
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] In many languages, some adjectives are *comparable* and the measure of comparison is called *degree*.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] For example, a person may be "polite", but another person may be "*more* polite", and a third person may be the "*most* polite" of the three.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] The word "more" here modifies the adjective "polite" to indicate a comparison is being made, and "most" modifies the adjective to indicate an absolute comparison (a *superlative*).
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] Among languages that allow adjectives to be compared, different means are used to indicate comparison.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] Some languages do not distinguish between comparative and superlative forms.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] Other languages allow adjectives to be compared but do not have a special comparative form of the adjective.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] In such cases, as in some Australian Aboriginal languages, case-marking, such as the ablative case, may be used to indicate one entity has more of an adjectival quality than (i.e.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] Another way to convey comparison is by incorporating the words "more" and "most".
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] There is no simple rule to decide which means is correct for any given adjective, however.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] The general tendency is for simpler adjectives and those from Anglo-Saxon to take the suffixes, while longer adjectives and those from French, Latin, or Greek do not—but sometimes the *sound* of the word is the deciding factor.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] Many adjectives do not naturally lend themselves to comparison.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] For example, some English speakers would argue that it does not make sense to say that one thing is "more ultimate" than another, or that something is "most ultimate", since the word "ultimate" is already absolute in its semantics.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] Such adjectives are called *non-comparable* or *absolute*.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] Nevertheless, native speakers will frequently play with the raised forms of adjectives of this sort.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] Although "pregnant" is logically non-comparable (either one is pregnant or not), one may hear a sentence like "She looks more and more pregnant each day".
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] Comparative and superlative forms are also occasionally used for other purposes than comparison.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] In Italian, superlatives are frequently used to put strong emphasis on an adjective: *bellissimo* means "most beautiful", but is in fact more commonly heard in the sense "extremely beautiful".
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] Attributive adjectives and other noun modifiers may be used either *restrictively* (helping to identify the noun's referent, hence "restricting" its reference) or *non-restrictively* (helping to describe a noun).
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] Here "difficult" is restrictive – it tells which tasks he avoids, distinguishing these from the easy ones: "Only those tasks that are difficult".
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] In English, restrictiveness is not marked on adjectives but is marked on relative clauses (the difference between "the man *who recognized me* was there" and "the man, *who recognized me*, was there" being one of restrictiveness).
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] In some languages, adjectives alter their form to reflect the gender, case and number of the noun that they describe.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] Here, a distinction may be made between attributive and predicative usage.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] In English, adjectives never agree, whereas in French, they always agree.
[src:agreement-linguistics/adjective] Semanticist Barbara Partee classifies adjectives semantically as intersective, subsective, or nonsubsective, with nonsubsective adjectives being plain nonsubsective or privative.
[src:agreement-linguistics/affix] In linguistics, an **affix** is a morpheme that is attached to a word stem to form a new word or word form.
[src:agreement-linguistics/affix] The two main categories are derivational and inflectional affixes.
[src:agreement-linguistics/affix] Derivational affixes, such as *un-*, *-ation*, *anti-*, and *pre-*, introduce a semantic change to the word they are attached to.
[src:agreement-linguistics/affix] Inflectional affixes introduce a syntactic change, such as singular into plural (e.g.
[src:agreement-linguistics/affix] *-(e)s*), or present simple tense into present continuous or past tense by adding *-ing* or *-ed* to an English word.
[src:agreement-linguistics/affix] All of them are bound morphemes by definition; prefixes and suffixes may be separable affixes.
[src:agreement-linguistics/affix] Adding a morpheme at the beginning of a word is called *prefixation*, in the middle *infixation*, and at the end *suffixation*.
[src:agreement-linguistics/affix] When marking text for interlinear glossing, as shown in the third column in the chart above, simple affixes such as prefixes and suffixes are separated from the stem with hyphens.
[src:agreement-linguistics/affix] Affixes that disrupt the stem, or that are themselves discontinuous, are often marked off with angle brackets.
[src:agreement-linguistics/affix] Reduplication is often shown with a tilde.
[src:agreement-linguistics/affix] Affixes which cannot be segmented are marked with a back slash.
[src:agreement-linguistics/affix] Semantically, lexical or semantic affixes often convey more general or abstract meanings than their corresponding free nouns.
[src:agreement-linguistics/affix] Lexical affixes are relatively rare and are used in Wakashan, Salishan, and Chimakuan languages — the presence of these is an areal feature of the Pacific Northwest of North America - where they show little to no resemblance to free nouns with similar meanings.
[src:agreement-linguistics/affix] Some linguists have claimed that these lexical suffixes provide only adverbial or adjectival notions to verbs.
[src:agreement-linguistics/affix] Other linguists disagree, arguing that they may additionally be syntactic arguments just as free nouns are and, thus, equating lexical suffixes with incorporated nouns.
[src:agreement-linguistics/affix] In sentence (1), the verb "wash" is **šak’ʷətəs** where **šak’ʷ-** is the root and **-ət** and **-əs** are inflectional suffixes.
[src:agreement-linguistics/affix] The subject "the woman" is **łə słeniʔ** and the object "the baby" is **łə qeq**.
[src:agreement-linguistics/affix] In this sentence, "the baby" is a free noun.
[src:agreement-linguistics/affix] In sentence (2), "baby" does not appear as a free noun.
[src:agreement-linguistics/affix] Instead it appears as the lexical suffix **-əyəł** which is affixed to the verb root **šk’ʷ-** (which has changed slightly in pronunciation, but this can also be ignored here).
[src:agreement-linguistics/affix] The lexical suffix is neither "the baby" (definite) nor "a baby" (indefinite); such referential changes are routine with incorporated nouns.
[src:agreement-linguistics/affix] In orthography, the terms for affixes may be used for the smaller elements of conjunct characters.
[src:agreement-linguistics/affix] For example, Maya glyphs are generally compounds of a *main sign* and smaller *affixes* joined at its margins.
[src:agreement-linguistics/affix] These are called *prefixes, superfixes, postfixes,* and *subfixes* according to their position to the left, on top, to the right, or at the bottom of the main glyph.
[src:agreement-linguistics/affix] A small glyph placed inside another is called an *infix.* Similar terminology is found with the conjunct consonants of the Indic alphabets.
[src:agreement-linguistics/affix] For example, the Tibetan alphabet utilizes prefix, suffix, superfix, and subfix consonant letters.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] For example, the sentences "*It exists.*" and "*They exist.*" are grammatically correct, while "*It exist.*" or "*They exists.*" are grammatically incorrect.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] English grammar requires that the verb and its subject agree in person: the pronoun *it* and the verb *exists* are singular, whereas the pronoun *they* and the verb *exist* are plural.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] In general, a verb's number is matched to its subject (which normally precedes the verb).
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] A singular subject takes a singular verb.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] The subject follows the verb in a range of constructions, including certain formal, literary, or emphatic structures as well as using *here* and *there* at the beginning of a sentence.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] When the subject is far from the verb, the verb is sometimes matched to the complement.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] This often occurs when the subject is a relative clause introduced by *what*, especially if the complement is long.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] Parentheses can always be removed, so they don't affect the agreement.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] When a noun is complex, i.e., it contains a preposition, prepositional phrase, adverb, adverbial phrase (e.g., *with*, *in addition to*, *along with*, *as well (as)*, *together with*, *besides*, or *not*), or a relative clause, the verb usually agrees with the head noun or pronoun.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] However, with quantifying expressions (phrases expressing parts), percentages, and fractions, the verb agrees with the noun or pronoun following *of*.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] A singular pronoun is used for a singular noun.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] A plural pronoun is used for a plural noun.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] *He* or *she* and *who* are normally used for people.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] When referring back to indefinite pronouns such as *somebody*, *someone*, *anybody*, *anyone*, *no one*, *nobody*, *everybody*, and *everyone*, the phrase *he or she* is used.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] Nowadays, it is also generally considered correct to use the word *they*.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] When animals are thought of as having personality, intelligence, or feelings, *he* or *she* may sometimes be used; this is common with pets.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] In such cases, *who* is used instead of *which*.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] Sometimes *she* is used for cars and motorcycles as well as countries, though *it* is more common in modern usage.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] Sailors often refer to ships and boats as *she*, but it's less common than it used to be.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] Some determiners are used only with certain kinds of nouns.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] For example, *this* and *that* change to *these* and *those* when the following noun is plural.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] The word *no* is followed by a singular noun when referring to the absence of even a single item.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] The word *no* is followed by a plural noun when referring to the absence of multiple items.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] After *kind/sort/type of*, a singular noun is usually used.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] It's also possible to use *kind/sort/type of* with a plural noun.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] The phrases *kinds/sorts/types of* can also be used with either a singular or a plural noun.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] Certain structures with *this*, *that*, *these*, and *those* occur, but they are considered incorrect.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] In formal style, a plural verb followed by *of this/that kind/sort/type* is also possible.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] The words *dozen*, *hundred*, *thousand*, *million*, and *billion* are used without the -s ending when they follow a number.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] Fractions between 1 and 2 are used with plural nouns.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] Expressions joined by *and* generally take a plural verb.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] If the nouns, however, suggest one idea or refer to the same thing or person, the verb is singular.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] When expressions joined by *and* follow *each* or *every*, the verb is singular.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] Expressions of distance, sums of money, periods of time, etc., regarded as one unit, take singular determiners, verbs, and pronouns.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] However, when these expressions are deemed separate individual units, they are plural.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] When speaking calculations, both singular and plural verbs are possible depending on the phrasing.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] In American English, collective nouns (e.g., team, club, committee) generally take singular verbs and either singular or plural pronouns.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] In British English, collective nouns may take either singular or plural verb and pronouns forms.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] Singular forms are used when the emphasis is on the group as a whole.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] In these cases *which* is also used as the relative pronoun.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] Plural forms are used when the emphasis is on the individual members.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] In those cases *who* is often used as the relative pronoun.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] As subjects, *another*, *anybody*, *anyone*, *anything*, *each*, *either*, *every*, *everybody*, *everyone*, *everything*, *less*, *little*, *much*, *neither*, *no one*, *nobody*, *nothing*, *one*, *somebody*, *someone*, and *something* take singular verbs.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] The pronouns *both*, *few*, *fewer*, *many*, *others*, and *several* take plural verbs.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] The pronouns *all*, *any*, *enough*, *more*, *most*, *none*, *some*, and *such* take a singular verb when they refer to an uncountable noun or a plural verb when they refer to a plural noun.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] The literal phrase *the number of* takes a singular verb, whereas the fixed phrase *a number of* is treated as plural.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] The same is true for *the total* and *a total of*.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] Titles and names (e.g., of countries, movies, restaurants, and quotations) referring to a single thing take singular verbs.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] Organization names that are plural may take singular or plural verbs and pronouns.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] In questions, *what* and *who* are followed by a singular verb when they are used as subject.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] However, when they are used as complements, they are followed by either a plural or singular verb.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] After *a pair of,* both singular and plural verbs can be used.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] Singular verbs are used with clauses used as subjects.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] When pronouns refer back to *everyone*, *everybody*, and *each* they may be singular (more formal) or plural (less formal).
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] When *each* refers to the subject and is in mid-position, plural nouns, pronouns, and verbs are used.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] The expression *more than one* uses a singular noun and verb.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] In informal style, *here's, there's, and where's* are often used with plural nouns (instead of *here are, there are, where are*); sometimes this is considered incorrect.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] After *any of*, *none of*, *either of*, *neither of*, and *each of*, English uses a plural personal pronoun or a plural determiner and noun and optionally a singular verb in formal style or a plural verb in informal style.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] After number followed by *in* or *out of*, English uses a number with a plural noun and either a singular or plural verb.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] The expression *one of* is usually followed by a plural noun.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] Sometimes *one of* is used with a singular noun referring to a group.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] After *one of* in the relative clauses, both plural and singular verbs are used; the plural form is generally considered correct.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] The phrase consisting of *the* and an adjective is plural when referring to well-known groups of people in a particular physical or social condition.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] In certain fixed, formal expressions, the phrase consisting of *the* and an adjective may be singular.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] The phrase consisting of *the* and an adjective is singular when it refers to general abstract ideas.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] The phrase consisting of *the* and an adjective is plural when referring to people from a specific country.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] The verb should agree with the expression in these structures closest to it (**the rule of proximity**).
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-in-the-english-language] Other forms of agreement occur, but they are not considered correct.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] In linguistics, **agreement** or **concord** (abbreviated **agr**) occurs when a word changes form depending on the other words to which it relates.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] It is an instance of inflection, and usually involves making the value of some grammatical category (such as gender or person) "agree" between varied words or parts of the sentence.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] For example, in Standard English, one may say *I am* or *he is*, but not "I is" or "he am".
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] This is because English grammar requires that the verb and its subject agree in *person*.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] The pronouns *I* and *he* are first and third person respectively, as are the verb forms *am* and *is*.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] The verb form must be selected so that it has the same person as the subject in contrast to notional agreement, which is based on meaning.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Agreement generally involves matching the value of some grammatical category between different constituents of a sentence (or sometimes between sentences, as in some cases where a pronoun is required to agree with its antecedent or referent).
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Some categories that commonly trigger grammatical agreement are noted below.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Agreement based on grammatical person is found mostly between verb and subject.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] *he is*) has been given in the introduction to this article.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Agreement between pronoun (or corresponding possessive adjective) and antecedent also requires the selection of the correct person.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] For example, if the antecedent is the first person noun phrase *Mary and I*, then a first person pronoun (*we/us/our*) is required; however, most noun phrases (*the dog*, *my cats*, *Jack and Jill*, etc.) are third person, and are replaced by a third person pronoun (*he/she/it/they* etc.).
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Agreement based on grammatical number can occur between verb and subject, as in the case of grammatical person discussed above.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] In fact the two categories are often conflated within verb conjugation patterns: there are specific verb forms for first person singular, second person plural and so on.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Agreement also occurs between nouns and their specifier and modifiers, in some situations.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] In languages in which grammatical gender plays a significant role, there is often agreement in gender between a noun and its modifiers.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Such agreement is also found with predicate adjectives: *l'homme est grand* ('the man is big') vs.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] *la chaise est grande* ('the chair is big').
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] In the case of verbs, gender agreement is less common, although it may still occur, for example in Arabic verbs where the second and third persons take different inflections for masculine and feminine subjects.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] In the French compound past tense, the past participle – formally an adjective – agrees in certain circumstances with the subject or with an object (see *passé composé* for details).
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] In Russian and most other Slavic languages, the form of the past tense agrees in gender with the subject, again due to derivation from an earlier adjectival construction.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] There is also agreement in gender between pronouns and their antecedents.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] In languages that have a system of cases, there is often agreement by case between a noun and its modifiers.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] In fact, the modifiers of nouns in languages such as German and Latin agree with their nouns in number, gender and case; all three categories are conflated together in paradigms of declension.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Case agreement is not a significant feature of English (only personal pronouns and the pronoun *who* have any case marking).
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] A rare type of agreement that phonologically copies parts of the head rather than agreeing with a grammatical category.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] In this example, what is copied is not a prefix, but rather the initial syllable of the head 'river'.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Languages can have no conventional agreement whatsoever, as in Japanese or Malay; barely any, as in English; a small amount, as in spoken French; a moderate amount, as in Greek or Latin; or a large amount, as in Swahili.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Modern English does not have a particularly large amount of agreement, although it is present.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] All regular verbs (and nearly all irregular ones) in English agree in the third-person singular of the present indicative by adding a suffix of either *-s* or *-es*.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] The latter is generally used after stems ending in the sibilants *sh*, *ch*, *ss,* or *zz* (e.g.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] There is a distinction between irregular verb conjugations in the spoken language and irregular spellings of words in the written language.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Linguistics generally concerns itself with the natural, spoken language, and not with spelling conventions in the written language.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] The verb *to go* is often given as an example of a verb with an irregular present tense conjugation, on account of adding "-es" instead of just "-s" for the third person singular conjugation.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] However, this is merely an arbitrary spelling convention.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] In the spoken language, the present tense conjugation of *to go* is entirely regular.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] If we were to classify *to go* as irregular based on the spelling of *goes*, then by the same reasoning, we would have to include other regular verbs with irregular spelling conventions such as *to veto/vetoes*, *to echo/echoes*, *to carry/carries*, *to hurry/hurries*, etc.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] In contrast, the verb *to do* is actually irregular in its spoken third-person singular conjugation, in addition to having a somewhat irregular spelling.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] While the verb *do* rhymes with *shoe*, its conjugation *does* does not rhyme with *shoes*; the verb *does* rhymes with *fuzz*.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Conversely, the verb *to say*, while it may appear to be regular based on its spelling, is in fact irregular in its third person singular present tense conjugation: *Say* is pronounced /seɪ/, but *says* is pronounced /sɛz/.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] *Say* rhymes with *pay*, but *says* does not rhyme with *pays*.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] The highly irregular verb *to be* is the only verb with more agreement than this in the present tense.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] In English, defective verbs generally show no agreement for person or number, they include the modal verbs: *can*, *may*, *shall*, *will*, *must*, *should*, *ought*.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] In Early Modern English agreement existed for the second person singular of all verbs in the present tense, as well as in the past tense of some common verbs.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] This was usually in the form *-est*, but *-st* and *-t* also occurred.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] This does not affect the endings for other persons and numbers.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Example present tense forms: *thou wilt*, *thou shalt*, *thou art*, *thou hast*, *thou canst*.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Note also the agreement shown by *to be* even in the subjunctive mood.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] However, for nearly all regular verbs, a separate *thou* form was no longer commonly used in the past tense.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Thus the auxiliary verb *to do* is used, e.g.*thou didst help*, not **thou helpedst*.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Indefinite pronouns like *one*, *all*, *everyone*, *everything*, *everybody*, *nothing*, *nobody*, *anyone*, *anything*, *anybody*, *another*, etc. are treated as singular (at least in formal written English).
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Exceptions: *None* is construed in the singular or plural as the sense may require, though the plural is commonly used.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] When *none* is clearly intended to mean *not one*, it should be followed by a singular verb.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] The SAT testing service, however, considers *none* to be strictly singular.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] The pronouns *neither* and *either* are singular although they seem to be referring to two things.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Words after *each*, *every*, and *many a* are treated as singular.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Exceptions: When the subject is followed by *each*, the verb agrees to the original subject.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] A measurement or quantity is treated as singular.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Exception: "Ten dollars were scattered on the floor" (meaning ten dollar bills).
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Exception: A fraction or percentage can be singular or plural based on the noun that follows it.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] A question with *who* or *what* takes a singular verb.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] A mathematical expression is treated as singular.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Two or more subjects joined by *and* take a plural verb.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Exceptions: If the nouns, however, suggest one idea or refer to the same thing or person, the verb is singular.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Exceptions: Words joined to a subject by *with*, *in addition to*, *along with*, *as well (as)*, *together with*, *besides*, *not*, etc. are parenthetical and the verb agrees with the original subject.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] A quantity expressing a certain number of items (e.g., *dozen*, *score*) is plural.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] A phrase of the form *the* + adjective is plural.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Some words appear singular but are plural: *police*, *cattle*, etc.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] When the word *enemy* is used in the sense of 'armed forces of another nation' a plural verb is used.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] When subjects are joined by *or*, *nor*, *not only ... but also*, etc. the verb agrees with the nearer subject.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] A collective noun is singular when thought of as a unit and plural when the individuals are considered.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Exceptions: British English, however, tends to treat team and company names as plural.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Phrases like *more than one*, *majority of* are singular or plural based on the noun it modifies.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Compared with English, Latin is an example of a highly inflected language.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Verbs must agree in person and number, and sometimes in gender, with their subjects.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Determiners and adjectives must agree in case, number and gender with the nouns they modify.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] In Latin, a pronoun such as *ego* and *tu* is only inserted for contrast and selection.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Proper nouns and common nouns functioning as subject are nonetheless frequent.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] For this reason, Latin is described as a null-subject language.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Spoken French always distinguishes the second person plural, and the first person plural in formal speech, from each other and from the rest of the present tense in all verbs in the first conjugation (infinitives in *-er*) other than *aller*.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] The first person plural form and pronoun (*nous*) are now usually replaced by the pronoun *on* (lit.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] 'one') and a third person singular verb form in Modern French.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Thus, *nous travaillons* (formal) becomes *on travaille*.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] In most verbs from the other conjugations, each person in the plural can be distinguished among themselves and from the singular forms, again, when using the traditional first person plural.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] The other endings that appear in written French (i.e.: all singular endings, and also the third person plural of verbs other than those with infinitives in *-er*) are often pronounced the same, except in liaison contexts.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Irregular verbs such as *être*, *faire*, *aller*, and *avoir* possess more distinctly pronounced agreement forms than regular verbs.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] The final S or T is silent, and the other three forms sound different from one another and from the singular forms.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Adjectives agree in gender and number with the nouns that they modify in French.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] As with verbs, the agreements are sometimes only shown in spelling since forms that are written with different agreement suffixes are sometimes pronounced the same (e.g.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] *joli*, *jolie*); although in many cases the final consonant is pronounced in feminine forms, but silent in masculine forms (e.g.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Most plural forms end in *-s*, but this consonant is only pronounced in liaison contexts, and it is determinants that help understand if the singular or plural is meant.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] The participles of verbs agree in gender and number with the subject or object in some instances.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Articles, possessives and other determinants also decline for number and (only in the singular) for gender, with plural determinants being the same for both genders.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Notice that some of the above also change (in the singular) if the following word begins with a vowel: *le* and *la* become *l'*, *du* and *de la* become *de l'*, *ma* becomes *mon* (as if the noun were masculine) and *ce* becomes *cet*.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] In Hungarian, verbs have polypersonal agreement, which means they agree with more than one of the verb's arguments: not only its subject but also its (accusative) object.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Difference is made between the case when there is a definite object and the case when the object is indefinite or there is no object at all.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Of course, nouns or pronouns may specify the exact object.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] In short, there is agreement between a verb and the person and number of its subject and the specificity of its object (which often refers to the person more or less exactly).
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] The predicate agrees in number with the subject and if it is copulative (i.e., it consists of a noun/adjective and a linking verb), both parts agree in number with the subject.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] For example: *A könyv**ek** érdekes**ek** volt**ak*** 'The books were interesting' (*a* 'the', *könyv* 'book', *érdekes* 'interesting', *voltak* 'were'): the plural is marked on the subject as well as both the adjectival and the copulative part of the predicate.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Within noun phrases, adjectives do not show agreement with the noun, though pronouns do. e.g.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] *a szép könyv**eitekkel*** 'with your nice books' (*szép* 'nice'): the suffixes of the plural, the possessive 'your' and the case marking 'with' are only marked on the noun.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] In the Scandinavian languages, adjectives (both attributive and predicative) are declined according to the gender, number, and definiteness of the noun they modify.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] In Icelandic and Faroese, adjectives are also declined according to grammatical case, unlike the other Scandinavian languages.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] In some cases in Swedish, Norwegian and Danish, adjectives and participles as predicates appear to disagree with their subjects.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] This phenomenon is referred to as pancake sentences.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] In Norwegian nynorsk, Swedish, Icelandic and Faroese the past participle must agree in gender, number and definiteness when the participle is in an attributive or predicative position.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] In Icelandic and Faroese, past participles would also have to agree in grammatical case.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] In Norwegian bokmål and Danish, past participles are only required to be declined in number and definiteness when in an attributive position.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Most Slavic languages are highly inflected, except for Bulgarian and Macedonian.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] The agreement is similar to Latin, for instance between adjectives and nouns in gender, number, case and animacy (if counted as a separate category).
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Verbs have six different forms in the present tense, for three persons in singular and plural.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] As in Latin, the subject is frequently dropped.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Swahili, like all other Bantu languages, has numerous noun classes.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Verbs must agree in class with their subjects and objects, and adjectives with the nouns that they qualify.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] For example: ***Ki**tabu **ki**moja **ki**tatosha* 'One book will be enough)', ***M**chungwa **m**moja **u**tatosha* 'One orange-tree will be enough', *Chungwa moja **li**tatosha* 'One orange will be enough'.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] For example: ***Vi**tabu **vi**wili **vi**tatosha* 'Two books will be enough', ***Mi**chungwa **mi**wili **i**tatosha* 'Two orange-trees will be enough', ***Ma**chungwa **ma**wili **ya**tatosha* 'Two oranges will be enough'.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Class and number are indicated with prefixes (or sometimes their absence), which are not always the same for nouns, adjectives and verbs, as illustrated by the examples.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Many sign languages have developed verb agreement with person.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] The American Sign Language (ASL) verb for 'see' (V handshape), moves from the subject to the object.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] In the case of a third-person subject, it goes from a location indexed to the subject to the object, and vice versa.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Also, in German Sign Language not all verbs are capable of subject/object verb agreement, so an auxiliary verb is used to convey this, carrying the meaning of the previous verb while still inflecting for person.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] In addition, some verbs also agree with the classifier the subject takes.
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] In the ASL verb for 'to be under', the classifier a verb takes goes under a downward-facing B handshape (palm facing downward).
[src:agreement-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] For example, if a person or an animal was crawled under something, a V handshape with bent fingers would go under the palm, but if it was a pencil, a 1-handshape (pointer finger out) would go under the palm.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] ASL originated in the early 19th century in the American School for the Deaf in Hartford, Connecticut, from a situation of language contact.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Since then, ASL use has been propagated widely by schools for the deaf and deaf community organizations.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Despite its wide use, no accurate count of ASL users has been taken.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Reliable estimates for American ASL users range from 250,000 to 500,000 persons, including a number of children of deaf adults (CODA) and other hearing individuals.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Signs in ASL have a number of phonemic components, such as movement of the face, the torso, shoulders, and the hands.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] ASL is not a form of pantomime, although iconicity plays a larger role in ASL than in spoken languages.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] English loan words are often borrowed through fingerspelling, although ASL grammar is unrelated to that of English.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] ASL has verbal agreement and aspectual marking and has a productive system of forming agglutinative classifiers.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Many linguists believe ASL to be a subject–verb–object language.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] However, there are several other proposals to account for ASL word order .
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] ASL emerged as a language at the American School for the Deaf, co-founded by Thomas Gallaudet and Laurent Clerc in 1817, which brought together Old French Sign Language, several indigenous sign languages, Martha's Vineyard sign language, and various home sign systems.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] ASL was created in that situation by language contact.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] ASL is influenced by its forerunners, yet linguistically distinct.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] The influence of French Sign Language (LSF) on ASL is readily apparent; for example, it has been found that about 58% of signs in modern ASL are cognates to Old French Sign Language signs.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] However, that is far less than the standard 80% measure used to determine whether related languages are actually dialects.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] That suggests nascent ASL was highly affected by the other signing systems brought by the ASD students although the school's original director, Laurent Clerc, taught in LSF.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] It has been proposed that ASL is a creole in which LSF is the superstrate language and the native indigenous sign languages are substrate languages.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] However, more recent research has shown that modern ASL does not share many of the structural features that characterize creole languages.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] ASL may have begun as a creole and then undergone structural change over time, but it is also possible that it was never a creole-type language to begin with.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] There are modality-specific reasons that signed languages tend towards agglutination, such as the ability to simultaneously convey information via the face, head, torso, and other body parts.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] That might override creole characteristics such as the tendency towards isolating morphology.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Additionally, Laurent Clerc and Thomas Hopkins Gallaudet may have used an artificially constructed form of manually coded language in instruction rather than true LSF.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Although the United States, the United Kingdom, and Australia share English as a common oral and written language, ASL is not mutually intelligible with either British Sign Language (BSL) or Auslan.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] All three languages show degrees of borrowing from English, but that alone is not sufficient for cross-language comprehension.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] However, that does not seem justified historically for ASL and Auslan, and it is likely that the resemblance is caused by the higher degree of iconicity in sign languages in general as well as contact with English.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] American Sign Language is growing in popularity in many states.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Many high school and university students desire to take it as a foreign language.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] This increased interest is also reflected beyond education, with ASL appearing more frequently in mainstream media through adaptations in film and popular media.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] ASL has also gained greater public visibility through social media and online platforms, where deaf and hard-of-hearing users share educational content and resources for learning the language.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Research on video-sharing platforms such as TikTok has found that there are opportunities for ASL users to create and distribute sign language content to wider audiences.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] ASL users, however, have a very distinct culture.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Their facial expressions and hand movements reflect what they are communicating.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] They also have their own sentence structure, which sets the language apart from other spoken and signed languages.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] ASL allows information to be expressed spatially, with meaning that is conveyed through the placement and movement of signs in relation to one another rather than through a strictly linear sequence.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] American Sign Language is now being accepted by many colleges as a language eligible for foreign language course credit; many states are making it mandatory to accept it as such.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] In some states however, this is only true with regard to high school coursework.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Organizations such as the American Sign Language Teachers Association support ASL education by providing professional development, certification and networking opportunities for teachers of ASL and Deaf Studies.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Prior to the birth of ASL, sign language had been used by various communities in the United States.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] In the United States, as elsewhere in the world, hearing families with deaf children have historically employed ad hoc home sign, which often reaches much higher levels of sophistication than gestures used by hearing people in spoken conversation.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] As early as 1541 at first contact by Francisco Vásquez de Coronado, there were reports that the Indigenous peoples of the Great Plains widely spoke a sign language to communicate across vast national and linguistic lines.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] In the 19th century, a "triangle" of indigenous sign languages developed in New England: one in Martha's Vineyard, Massachusetts; one in Henniker, New Hampshire, and one in Sandy River Valley, Maine.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Martha's Vineyard Sign Language (MVSL), which was particularly important for the history of ASL, was used mainly in Chilmark, Massachusetts.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Due to intermarriage in the original community of English settlers of the 1690s, and the recessive nature of genetic deafness, Chilmark had a high 4% rate of genetic deafness.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] MVSL was used even by hearing residents whenever a deaf person was present, and also in some situations where spoken language would be ineffective or inappropriate, such as during church sermons or between boats at sea.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] ASL is thought to have originated in the American School for the Deaf, founded in Hartford, Connecticut, in 1817.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Originally known as *The American Asylum, At Hartford, For The Education And Instruction Of The Deaf And Dumb*, the school was founded by the Yale graduate and divinity student Thomas Hopkins Gallaudet.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Gallaudet, inspired by his success in demonstrating the learning abilities of a young deaf girl Alice Cogswell, traveled to Europe in order to learn deaf pedagogy from European institutions.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Ultimately, Gallaudet chose to adopt the methods of the French Institut National de Jeunes Sourds de Paris, and convinced Laurent Clerc, an assistant to the school's founder Charles-Michel de l'Épée, to accompany him back to the United States.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Upon his return, Gallaudet and Clerc founded the ASD on April 15, 1817.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] In 2019, April 15 was declared as the National American Sign Language Day.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] The largest group of students during the first seven decades of the school were from Martha's Vineyard, and they brought MVSL with them.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] There were also 44 students from around Henniker, New Hampshire, and 27 from the Sandy River valley in Maine, each of which had their own village sign language.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Other students brought knowledge of their own home signs.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Laurent Clerc, the first teacher at ASD, taught using French Sign Language (LSF), which itself had developed in the Parisian school for the deaf established in 1755.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] From that situation of language contact, a new language emerged, now known as ASL.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] More schools for the deaf were founded after ASD, and knowledge of ASL spread to those schools.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] In addition, the rise of deaf community organizations bolstered the continued use of ASL.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Societies such as the National Association of the Deaf and the National Fraternal Society of the Deaf held national conventions that attracted signers from across the country.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] All of that contributed to ASL's wide use over a large geographical area, atypical of a sign language.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] While oralism, an approach to educating deaf students focusing on oral language, had previously been used in American schools, the Milan Congress of 1880 made it dominant and effectively banned the use of sign languages at schools in the United States and Europe.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Nevertheless, oralism remained a predominant method of deaf education up to the 1950s.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] In response to the Milan Conference, the National Association for the Deaf (NAD) was established.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] As an additional response to the Milan Conference of 1880, the NAD created "Preservation of Sign Language" silent film was made to preserve the language.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] These films have been preserved in the US Library of Congress.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] In the past, linguists did not consider American Sign Language to be true "language" but as something inferior.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Recognition of the legitimacy of ASL was achieved by William Stokoe, a linguist who arrived at Gallaudet University in 1955 when that was still the dominant assumption.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Aided by the Civil Rights Movement of the 1960s, Stokoe argued for manualism, the use of sign language in deaf education.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Stokoe noted that American Sign Language shares the important features that oral languages have as a means of communication, and even devised a transcription system for ASL.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] In doing so, Stokoe revolutionized both deaf education and linguistics.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] In the 1960s, ASL was sometimes referred to as "Ameslan", but that term is now considered obsolete.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Counting the number of ASL signers is difficult because ASL users have never been counted by the American census.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] There have been proposals to add ASL as a language people could report they know other than English on the US census, but this was not listed as a language option on the census of 2020.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] The ultimate source for current estimates of the number of ASL users in the United States is a report for the National Census of the Deaf Population (NCDP) by Schein and Delk (1974).
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Based on a 1972 survey of the NCDP, Schein and Delk provided estimates consistent with a signing population between 250,000 and 500,000.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] The survey did not distinguish between ASL and other forms of signing; in fact, the name "ASL" was not yet in widespread use.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Incorrect figures are sometimes cited for the population of ASL users in the United States based on misunderstandings of known statistics.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Demographics of the deaf population have been confused with those of ASL use since adults who become deaf late in life rarely use ASL in the home.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] That accounts for currently-cited estimations that are greater than 500,000; such mistaken estimations can reach as high as 15,000,000.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] A 100,000-person lower bound has been cited for ASL users; the source of that figure is unclear, but it may be an estimate of prelingual deafness, which is when a person is found to have hearing loss prior to acquiring their first language.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] ASL is sometimes incorrectly cited as the third- or fourth-most-spoken language in the United States.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Those figures misquote Schein and Delk (1974), who actually concluded that ASL speakers constituted the third-largest population "requiring an interpreter in court".
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Although that would make ASL the third-most used language among monolinguals other than English, it does not imply that it is the fourth-most-spoken language in the United States since speakers of other languages may also speak English.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] That contrasts with Europe, where a variety of sign languages are used within the same continent.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] The unique situation of ASL seems to have been caused by the proliferation of ASL through schools influenced by the American School for the Deaf, wherein ASL originated, and the rise of community organizations for the deaf.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Throughout West Africa, ASL-based sign languages are signed by educated deaf adults.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Such languages, imported by boarding schools, are often considered by associations to be the official sign languages of their countries and are named accordingly, such as Nigerian Sign Language and Ghanaian Sign Language.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Such signing systems are found in Benin, Burkina Faso, Ivory Coast, Ghana, Liberia, Mauritania, Mali, Nigeria, and Togo.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Due to lack of data, it is still an open question how similar those sign languages are to ASL used in America.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] ASL is also widely learned as a second language for many deaf people in the world.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] American Sign Language production can vary according to location, which is also known as regional variation.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Regional Variation is natural and common among many signed and spoken languages.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Signers from the American South tend to sign with more flow and ease.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Native signers from New York have been reported as signing comparatively quicker and sharper.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Sign production of native Californian signers has also been reported as being fast.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Research on that phenomenon often concludes that the fast-paced production for signers from the coasts could be due to the fast-paced nature of living in large metropolitan areas.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] That conclusion also supports how the ease with which Southerners sign could be caused by the easygoing environment of the American South in comparison to that of the coasts.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Sign production can also vary depending on age and native language.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] For example, sign production of letters may vary in older signers.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Slight differences in fingerspelling production can be a signal of age.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Additionally, signers who learned American Sign Language as a second language vary in production.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] For deaf signers who learned a different sign language before learning American Sign Language, qualities of their native language may show in their ASL production.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Some examples of that varied production include fingerspelling towards the body, instead of away from it, and signing certain movement from bottom to top, instead of top to bottom.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Hearing people who learn American Sign Language also have noticeable differences in signing production.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] The most notable production difference of hearing people learning American Sign Language is their rhythm and arm posture.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Most popularly, there are variants of the signs for words such as "birthday", "pizza", "Halloween", "early", and "soon", just a sample of the most commonly recognized signs with variants based on regional change.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] The sign for "school" is commonly varied between black and white signers due to previously segregated schools for the deaf.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] The rationally segregated schools lead to the development of two separate signed language varieties.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Research is being done to see if Black American Sign Language (BASL) is its own separate language from ASL or a dialect.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Social variation is also found between citation forms and forms used by deaf gay men for words such as "pain" and "protest".
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] The prevalence of residential deaf schools can account for the slight regional variance of signs and sign productions across the United States.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Deaf schools often serve students of the state in which the school resides.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] It is hypothesized that because of there being one or only a few deaf residential schools for the deaf, certain variants of a sign prevailed over others due to the choice of variant used by the student of the school/signers in the community.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Prior to the invention of the internet, there was limited access to signers from other regions; however, this has changed with the invention of internet and the ability to view signs online.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] However, American Sign Language does not appear to be vastly varied in comparison to other signed languages.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Varieties of ASL are found throughout the world.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] There is little difficulty in comprehension among the varieties of the United States and Canada.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] *A Loss for Words: The Story of Deafness in a Family*.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Mutual intelligibility among those ASL varieties is high, and the variation is primarily lexical.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] For example, there are three different words for English *about* in Canadian ASL; the standard way, and two regional variations (Atlantic and Ontario).
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Variation may also be phonological, meaning that the same sign may be signed in a different way depending on the region.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] For example, an extremely common type of variation is between the handshapes /1/, /L/, and /5/ in signs with one handshape.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] There is also a distinct variety of ASL used by the Black deaf community.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Black ASL evolved as a result of racially segregated schools in some states, which included the residential schools for the deaf.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Black ASL differs from standard ASL in vocabulary, phonology, and some grammatical structure.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] While African American English (AAE) is generally viewed as more innovating than standard English, Black ASL is more conservative than standard ASL, preserving older forms of many signs.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Black sign language speakers use more two-handed signs than in mainstream ASL, are less likely to show assimilatory lowering of signs produced on the forehead (e.g.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Modern Black ASL borrows a number of idioms from AAE; for instance, the AAE idiom "I feel you" is calqued into Black ASL.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] ASL is used internationally as a lingua franca, and a number of closely related sign languages derived from ASL are used in many different countries.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Even so, there have been varying degrees of divergence from standard ASL in those imported ASL varieties.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Bolivian Sign Language is reported to be a dialect of ASL, no more divergent than other acknowledged dialects.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] On the other hand, it is also known that some imported ASL varieties have diverged to the extent of being separate languages.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] For example, Malaysian Sign Language, which has ASL origins, is no longer mutually comprehensible with ASL and must be considered its own language.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] For some imported ASL varieties, such as those used in West Africa, it is still an open question how similar they are to ASL.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] When communicating with hearing English speakers, ASL-speakers often use what is commonly called Pidgin Signed English (PSE) or 'contact signing', a blend of English structure with ASL vocabulary.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] However, there are modes of communication that are not officially a language such as Manual Code of English, such as Pidgin Signed English or Contact Sign, Signing Exact English.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] To codeswitch for not fluent ASL users, some deaf people use some of these modes of communication to help hearing people understand.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Various types of PSE exist, ranging from highly English-influenced PSE (practically relexified English) to PSE which is quite close to ASL lexically and grammatically, but may alter some subtle features of ASL grammar.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Fingerspelling may be used more often in PSE than it is normally used in ASL.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] There have been some constructed sign languages, known as Manually Coded English (MCE), which match English grammar exactly and simply replace spoken words with signs; those systems are not considered to be varieties of ASL.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Tactile ASL (TASL) is a variety of ASL used throughout the United States by and with the DeafBlind.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] It is particularly common among those with Usher's syndrome 1.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] It results in deafness from birth followed by loss of vision later in life; consequently, those with Usher's syndrome 1 often grow up in the deaf community using ASL, and later transition to TASL.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Usher syndrome 2 is when someone is born with deafness and low vision.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Both types of Usher's Syndrome could result in the DeafBlind person preferring to muse TASL as a method of communication.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] TASL differs from ASL in that signs are produced by touching the palms, and there are some grammatical differences from standard ASL in order to compensate for the lack of nonmanual signing.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] ASL changes over time and from generation to generation.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] The sign for telephone has changed as the shape of phones and the manner of holding them have changed.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] The development of telephones with screens has also changed ASL, encouraging the use of signs that can be seen on small screens.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] In 2013, the White House published a response to a petition that gained over 37,000 signatures to *officially recognize American Sign Language as a community language and a language of instruction in schools*.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] The response is titled "there shouldn't be any stigma about American Sign Language" and addressed that ASL is a vital language for the deaf and hard of hearing.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Stigmas associated with sign languages and the use of sign for educating children often lead to the absence of sign during periods in children's lives when they can access languages most effectively.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Benedict advocate not only for bilingualism (using ASL and English training) but also for early childhood intervention for children who are deaf.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] York University psychologist Ellen Bialystok has also campaigned for bilingualism, arguing that those who are bilingual acquire cognitive skills that may help to prevent dementia later in life.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Most children born to deaf parents are hearing and are also known as CODAs ("Children of Deaf Adults").
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Some CODAs acquire ASL as well as deaf cultural values and behaviors from birth from their deaf parents.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Such bilingual hearing children may be mistakenly labeled as being "slow learners" or as having "language difficulties" because of preferential attitudes towards spoken language.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Although there is no well-established writing system for ASL, written sign language dates back almost two centuries.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] The first systematic writing system for a sign language seems to be that of Roch-Ambroise Auguste Bébian, developed in 1825.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] However, written sign language remained marginal among the public.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] In the 1960s, linguist William Stokoe created Stokoe notation specifically for ASL.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] It is alphabetic, with a letter or diacritic for every phonemic (distinctive) hand shape, orientation, motion, and position, though it lacks any representation of facial expression, and is better suited for individual words than for extended passages of text.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Stokoe used that system for his 1965 *A Dictionary of American Sign Language on Linguistic Principles*.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] SignWriting, proposed in 1974 by Valerie Sutton, is the first writing system to gain use among the public and the first writing system for sign languages to be included in the Unicode Standard.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] SignWriting consists of more than 5000 distinct iconic graphs/glyphs.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Currently, it is in use in many schools for the deaf, particularly in Brazil, and has been used in International Sign forums with speakers and researchers in more than 40 countries, including Brazil, Ethiopia, France, Germany, Italy, Portugal, Saudi Arabia, Slovenia, Tunisia, and the United States.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Sutton SignWriting has both a printed and an electronically produced form so that persons can use the system anywhere that oral languages are written (personal letters, newspapers, and media, academic research).
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] The systematic examination of the International Sign Writing Alphabet (ISWA) as an equivalent usage structure to the International Phonetic Alphabet for spoken languages has been proposed.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] According to some researchers, SignWriting is not a phonemic orthography and does not have a one-to-one map from phonological forms to written forms.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] That assertion has been disputed, and the process for each country to look at the ISWA and create a phonemic/morphemic assignment of features of each sign language was proposed by researchers Msc.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Roberto Cesar Reis da Costa and Madson Barreto in a thesis forum on June 23, 2014.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] The SignWriting community has an open project on Wikimedia Labs to support the various Wikimedia projects on Wikimedia Incubator and elsewhere involving SignWriting.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] The ASL Wikipedia request was marked as eligible in 2008 and the test ASL Wikipedia has 50 articles written in ASL using SignWriting.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] The most widely used transcription system among academics is HamNoSys, developed at the University of Hamburg.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Based on Stokoe Notation, HamNoSys was expanded to about 200 graphs in order to allow transcription of any sign language.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Phonological features are usually indicated with single symbols, though the group of features that make up a handshape is indicated collectively with a symbol.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Several additional candidates for written ASL have appeared over the years, including SignFont, ASL-phabet, and Si5s.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] For English-speaking audiences, ASL is often glossed using English words.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Such glosses are typically all-capitalized and are arranged in ASL order.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] For example, the ASL sentence *DOG NOW CHASE>IX=3 CAT*, meaning "the dog is chasing the cat", uses NOW to mark ASL progressive aspect and shows ASL verbal inflection for the third person (*>IX=3*).
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] However, glossing is not used to write the language for speakers of ASL.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Each sign in ASL is composed of a number of distinctive components, generally referred to as parameters.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] All signs can be described using the five parameters involved in signed languages, which are handshape, movement, palm orientation, location and nonmanual markers.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Just as phonemes of sound distinguish meaning in spoken languages, those parameters are the phonemes that distinguish meaning in signed languages like ASL.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] There are also meaningful nonmanual signals in ASL, which may include movement of the eyebrows, the cheeks, the nose, the head, the torso, and the eyes.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] These nonmanual features can indicate grammatical properties of the language.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] William Stokoe proposed that such components are analogous to the phonemes of spoken languages.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] There has also been a proposal that they are analogous to classes like place and manner of articulation.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] As in spoken languages, those phonological units can be split into distinctive features.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] For instance, the handshapes /2/ and /3/ are distinguished by the presence or absence of the feature [± closed thumb], as illustrated to the right.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] ASL has processes of allophony and phonotactic restrictions.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] There is ongoing research into whether ASL has an analog of syllables in spoken language.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] ASL has a rich system of verbal inflection, which involves both grammatical aspect: how the action of verbs flows in time—and agreement marking.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Aspect can be marked by changing the manner of movement of the verb; for example, continuous aspect is marked by incorporating rhythmic, circular movement, while punctual aspect is achieved by modifying the sign so that it has a stationary hand position.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Verbs must agree with both the subject and the object, and are marked for number and reciprocity.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Reciprocity is indicated by using two one-handed signs; for example, the sign SHOOT, made with an L-shaped handshape with inward movement of the thumb, inflects to SHOOT[reciprocal], articulated by having two L-shaped hands "shooting" at each other.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] ASL has a productive system of classifiers, which are used to classify objects, their size and shape, and their movement in space.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] In the past, classifiers were known as Size and Shape Specifiers (SaSSes).
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] For example, a rabbit running downhill would use a classifier consisting of a bent V classifier handshape with a downhill-directed path; if the rabbit is hopping, the path is executed with a bouncy manner.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] In general, classifiers are composed of a "classifier handshape" bound to a "movement root".
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] The classifier handshape represents the object as a whole, incorporating such attributes as surface, depth, and shape, and is usually very iconic.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] The movement root consists of a path, a direction and a manner.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Fingerspelling is a way in which sign languages manually represent the written systems of ambient languages of which they have frequent language contact.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Orthographic symbols of those contact languages are represented through fingerspelling systems in sign languages.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Fingerspelling systems vary cross-linguistically in how they accommodate their ambient written systems, just as much as the written systems vary cross-linguistically themselves.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] For example, in American Sign Language, a one-handed fingerspelled system reflects the symbols of the Roman alphabet which is also used in many other signed languages around the world, mostly in Europe.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] In British Sign Language, the fingerspelled symbols represent the Roman alphabet but a two-handed system is used.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] In Japan, a one-handed system is used but the symbols represent a syllabary orthographic system.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Fingerspelled words can be used for numerous reasons, including but not limited to: proper nouns, emphasis, representation of loan words etc..
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] ASL is a subject–verb–object (SVO) language, but various phenomena affect that basic word order.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] However, other word orders may also occur since ASL allows the topic of a sentence to be moved to sentence-initial position, a phenomenon known as topicalization.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] ASL also allows null subject sentences whose subject is implied, rather than stated explicitly.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Topicalization, accompanied with a null subject and a subject copy, can produce yet another word order, object–verb–subject (OVS).
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Those properties of ASL allow it a variety of word orders, leading many to question which is the true, underlying, "basic" order.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] There are several other proposals that attempt to account for the flexibility of word order in ASL.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] One proposal is that languages like ASL are best described with a topic–comment structure whose words are ordered by their importance in the sentence, rather than by their syntactic properties.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Another hypothesis is that ASL exhibits free word order, in which syntax is not encoded in word order but can be encoded by other means such as head nods, eyebrow movement, and body position.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] The American with Disabilities Act (ADA) requires public facilities to provide auxiliary aid such as sign language interpreters.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Currently there is a database, the National Registry of Interpreters for the Deaf, to get qualified interpreters.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Sign language interpreters are important for the Deaf and hard-of-hearing community to provide equal access to information in places that may not have written versions like concerts, education, and healthcare.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Not many places have interpreters available on call, with a 50:1 ratio of Deaf or hard-of-hearing person to ASL interpreter.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] This creates barriers for the Deaf community when looking at the social model of disability.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Professional certification can be hard to obtain, and public facilities do not have to provide accommodation if it affects the service or becomes a burden.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Common misconceptions are that signs are iconically self-explanatory, that they are a transparent imitation of what they mean, or even that they are pantomime.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] In fact, many signs bear no resemblance to their referent because they were originally arbitrary symbols, or their iconicity has been obscured over time.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Even so, in ASL iconicity plays a significant role; a high percentage of signs resemble their referents in some way.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] That may be because the medium of sign, three-dimensional space, naturally allows more iconicity than oral language.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] In the era of the influential linguist Ferdinand de Saussure, it was assumed that the mapping between form and meaning in language must be completely arbitrary.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Although onomatopoeia is a clear exception, since words like "choo-choo" bear clear resemblance to the sounds that they mimic, the Saussurean approach was to treat them as marginal exceptions.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] ASL, with its significant inventory of iconic signs, directly challenges that theory.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] Research on acquisition of pronouns in ASL has shown that children do not always take advantage of the iconic properties of signs when they interpret their meaning.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] It has been found that when children acquire the pronoun "you", the iconicity of the point (at the child) is often confused, being treated more like a name.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] That is a similar finding to research in oral languages on pronoun acquisition.
[src:agreement-linguistics/american-sign-language] It has also been found that iconicity of signs does not affect immediate memory and recall; less iconic signs are remembered just as well as highly-iconic signs.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] Concepts of animacy constantly vary beyond a simple animate and inanimate binary; many languages function off an hierarchical general animacy scale that ranks animacy as a "matter of gradience".
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] Typically (with some variation of order and of where the cutoff for animacy occurs), the scale ranks humans above animals, then plants, natural forces, concrete objects, and abstract objects, in that order.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] In referring to humans, this scale contains a hierarchy of persons, ranking the first- and second-person pronouns above the third person, partly a product of empathy, involving the speaker and interlocutor.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] It is obvious that the ability to distinguish between animate and inanimate is very important from an evolutionary point of view.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] In order to survive, an animal must be able to quickly and accurately distinguish between its sexual partners, rivals, predators, animals that it eats, etc., and inanimate objects.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] As for people, the ability to distinguish between animate and inanimate arises in infancy, even before children have mastered speech.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] Apparently, there is a brain mechanism responsible for this process.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] De Swart and de Hoop (2018) emphasize the importance of distinguishing between three types of animacy: biological, conceptual, and grammatical.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] Each of these types plays a unique role in understanding how humans perceive and express the distinction between animate and inanimate entities.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] Biological animacy refers to entities that are biologically alive and is defined by physical properties like the capacity to die.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] Conceptual animacy is based on the speaker's perception and cultural background.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] It concerns what is perceived as alive, influenced by the "ego's" perspective and societal beliefs.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] This type often diverges from biological animacy.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] For example, in some cultures or languages, inanimate objects like the sun or mountains are considered "animate" due to mythology or cultural beliefs.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] Another example is the term *bot*, which is animate in many languages due to human-like behavior of a bot.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] Conceptual animacy reflects how humans personify or attribute agency to non-living entities.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] Grammatical animacy demonstrates how biological and conceptual animacy are represented in the grammar of languages.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] It operates as a semantic feature or condition influencing linguistic structures, such as verb agreement or case marking.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] For instance, in Russian, animacy distinctions affect object marking in sentences; animate nouns, such as humans and animals, are treated differently than inanimate nouns.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] This type of animacy illustrates the interaction between cognitive perceptions and linguistic systems.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] The animacy hierarchy (e.g., human > animal > inanimate) is widely applied in linguistic analysis to explain various phenomena.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] Animate entities are more likely to act as agents or subjects in sentences (agentivity), receive distinct grammatical treatment in case marking or agreement, and be referenced explicitly in discourse.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] Additionally, animacy hierarchies are not static; cultural factors or temporary discourse contexts can shift these classifications.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] Although animacy distinctions appear universally across languages, their specific implementation varies.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] For example, Navajo uses animacy to govern verb marking, while Slavic languages reflect animacy distinctions in noun declensions.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] However, the universality of animacy as a linguistic feature is debated due to its variability across languages.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] Cultural and functional factors can lead to unique animacy hierarchies, showing that animacy is both a universal and context-dependent concept.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] The distinction between *he*, *she*, and other personal pronouns, on one hand, and *it*, on the other hand is a distinction in animacy in English and in many Indo-European languages.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] The same can be said about distinction between *who* and *what*.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] Some languages, such as Turkish, Georgian, spoken Finnish and Italian, do not distinguish between *s/he* and *it*.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] In Finnish, there is a distinction in animacy between *hän*, "he/she", and *se*, "it", but in spoken Finnish **se** can mean "he/she".
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] English shows a similar lack of distinction between *they* animate and *they* inanimate in the plural.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] There is another example of how animacy plays some role in English.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] Examples of languages in which an animacy hierarchy is important include the Totonac language in Mexico and the Southern Athabaskan languages (such as Western Apache and Navajo) whose animacy hierarchy has been the subject of intense study.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] The Tamil language has a noun classification based on animacy.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] The distinction was preserved in Anatolian languages like Hittite, all of which are now extinct.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] The animate gender would then later, after the separation of the Anatolian languages, have developed into the feminine and masculine genders.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] The plural of neuter/inanimate nouns is believed to have had the same ending as collective nouns in the singular, and some words with the collective noun ending in singular were later to become words with the feminine gender.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] Traces can be found in Ancient Greek in which the singular form of verbs was used when they referred to neuter words in plural.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] In many Indo-European languages, such as Latin and the Slavic languages, the plural ending of many neuter words in the merged nominative–accusative–vocative corresponds to the feminine singular nominative form.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] Like most other Athabaskan languages, Southern Athabaskan languages show various levels of animacy in their grammar, with certain nouns taking specific verb forms according to their rank in this animacy hierarchy.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] Generally, the most animate noun in a sentence must occur first while the noun with lesser animacy occurs second.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] If both nouns are equal in animacy, either noun can occur in the first position.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] The *yi-* prefix on the verb indicates that the first noun is the subject and *bi-* indicates that the second noun is the subject.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] There is evidence suggesting that the word order itself is not the important factor.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] Instead, the verb construction usually interpreted as the passive voice (e.g.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] "the girl was pecked by the bird") instead indicates that the more animate noun allowed the less animate noun to perform the action (e.g.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] "the girl let herself be pecked by the bird").
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] The idea is that things ranked higher in animacy are presumed to be in control of the situation, and that the less-animate thing can only act if the more-animate thing permits it.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] Although nouns in Japanese are not marked for animacy, it has two existential/possessive verbs; one for implicitly animate nouns (usually humans and animals) and one for implicitly inanimate nouns (often non-living objects and plants).
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] The verb *iru* (いる, also written 居る) is used to show the existence or possession of an animate noun.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] The verb *aru* (ある, sometimes written 在る when existential or 有る when possessive) is used to show the existence or possession of an inanimate noun.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] An animate noun, here 'cat', is marked as the subject of the verb with the subject particle *ga* (が), but no topic or location is marked.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] That implies the noun is indefinite and merely exists.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] In the second example, a topic is introduced, in this case "I", with the topic particle *wa* (は).
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] The animate noun is again marked with a subject particle, and no location is denoted.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] That implies that the topic owns or is holding onto the noun.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] In the third example, the noun is marked as the topic (and by default functions as the subject of the verb) while a location, here the top of a chair, is marked with the location particle *ni* (に).
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] That implies that the noun is a definite noun and is at the specified location.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] In all these cases, if the noun is not animate, such as a stone, instead of a cat, the verb *iru* must be replaced with the verb *aru* (ある or 有る [possessive] / 在る [existential, locative]).
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] 'There is a robot' (emphasis on its human-like behavior).
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] 'There is a robot' (emphasis on its status as a nonliving thing).
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] The Ryukyuan languages, spoken in the Ryukyu Islands, agree in animacy in their case systems.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] Middle Korean has genitive particles that were used differently depends on a noun's animacy.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] For an inanimate noun, the particle "-ㅅ" (-s) was used as the inanimate noun's genitive.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] Slavic languages that have case (all of them except Bulgarian and Macedonian) have a somewhat complex hierarchy of animacy in which syntactically animate nouns may include both animate and inanimate objects (like mushrooms and dances).
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] Overall, the border between animate and inanimate places humans and animals in the former and plants, etc., in the latter, thus basing itself more so on sentience than life.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] Animacy functions as a subgender through which noun cases intersect in a phenomenon called syncretism, which here can be either nominative-accusative or genitive-accusative.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] Inanimate nouns have accusative forms that take on the same forms as their nominative, with animate nouns marked by having their accusative forms resemble the genitive.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] That syncretism also occurs when restricted by declension class, resulting in syncretism in multiple pronominal forms, such as the Russian reflexive pronoun себя (*sebja*), personal pronouns, and the indefinite interrogative and relative pronoun *kto*.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] Elsewhere, animacy is displayed syntactically, such as in endings of modifiers for masc nouns of the second declension.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] While animacy is viewed as primarily semantic when approached diachronically, a synchronic view suggests animacy as a sublevel of gender.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] Syntactic gender is defined through patterns in agreement, not necessarily semantic value.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] For example, Russian has "common gender" nouns that refer to traditionally masculine roles but act as syntactically feminine.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] Animacy occurs as a subgender of nouns and modifiers (and pronouns only when adjectival) and is primarily reflected in modifier-head agreement (as opposed to subject-predicate agreement).
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] Some consider the system to be based on marking inanimacy in which case the gen-acc distinguishes a "non-inanimate" subgender of nouns and modifiers, and others claim that ultimately it is indeed animacy that is marked.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] The usage is standard and is found around the Spanish-speaking world.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] Spanish personal pronouns are generally omitted if the subject of the sentence is obvious, but when they are explicitly stated, they are used only with people or humanized animals or things.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] The inanimate subject pronoun in Spanish is *ello*, like *it* in English (except "ello" can only be used to refer to verbs and clauses, not objects, as all nouns are either masculine or feminine and are referred to with the appropriate pronouns).
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] Spanish direct-object pronouns (*me, te, lo, la, se, nos, os, los, las*) do not differentiate between animate and inanimate entities, and only the third persons have a gender distinction.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] Thus, for example, the third-person singular feminine pronoun, *la*, could refer to a woman, an animal (like *mariposa*, butterfly), or an object (like *casa*, house), if their genders are feminine.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] In certain dialects, there is a tendency to use *le* (which is usually an indirect object pronoun, meaning "to him/her") as a direct-object pronoun, at the expense of the direct-object pronouns *lo/la*, if the referent is animate.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] That tendency is especially strong if (a) the pronoun is being used as a special second-person pronoun of respect, (b) the referent is male, (c) certain verbs are used, (d) the subject of the verb happens to be inanimate.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] In Classical and Modern Standard Arabic and some other varieties of Arabic, animacy has a limited application in the agreement of plural and dual nouns with verbs and adjectives.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] Verbs follow nouns in plural agreement only when the verb comes after the subject.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] When a verb comes before an explicit subject, the verb is always singular.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] Also, only animate plural and dual nouns take plural agreement; inanimate plural nouns are always analyzed as singular feminine or plural feminine for the purpose of agreement.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] Thus, Arabic المهندسون يطيرون إلى ألمانيا (*Al-muhandisūn yaṭīrūn 'ilā 'Almāniyā*, "The engineers fly to Germany") is masculine plural agreement, but الطائرات تطير إلى ألمانيا (*Al-ṭā'irāt taṭīr 'ilā 'Almāniyā*, "The planes fly to Germany") is feminine singular.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] In general, Arabic divides animacy between عاقل (thinking, or rational) and غير عاقل (unthinking, or irrational).
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] Animals fall in the latter category, but their status may change depending on the usage, especially with personification.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] Animacy can also condition the nature of the morphologies of split-ergative languages.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] In such languages, participants more animate are more likely to be the agent of the verb, and therefore are marked in an accusative pattern: unmarked in the agent role and marked in the patient or oblique role.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] Likewise, less animate participants are inherently more patient-like, and take ergative marking: unmarked when in the patient role and marked when in the agent role.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] In a direct–inverse language, clauses with transitive verbs can be expressed with either a direct or an inverse construction.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] The direct construction is used when the subject of the transitive clause outranks the object in salience or animacy.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] The inverse construction is used when the "notional object" outranks the "notional subject".
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] A noun essentially requires the traits of animacy in order to receive the role of Actor and Experiencer.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] Additionally, the Agent role is generally assigned to the NP with highest ranking in the animacy hierarchy – ultimately, only animate beings can function as true agents.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] Similarly, languages universally tend to place animate nouns earlier in the sentence than inanimate nouns.
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] Animacy is a key component of agency – combined with other factors like "awareness of action".
[src:agreement-linguistics/animacy] Agency and animacy are intrinsically linked – with each as a "conceptual property" of the other.
[src:agreement-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] In grammar, an **antecedent** is one or more words that identifies a pronoun or other pro-form.
[src:agreement-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] For example, in the sentence "John arrived late because traffic held him up," the word "John" is the antecedent of the pronoun "him." Pro-forms usually follow their antecedents, but sometimes precede them.
[src:agreement-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] In the latter case, the more accurate term would technically be *postcedent*, although this term is not commonly distinguished from *antecedent* because the definition of *antecedent* usually encompasses it.
[src:agreement-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] The linguistic term that is closely related to *antecedent* and *pro-form* is *anaphora*.
[src:agreement-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] Theories of syntax explore the distinction between antecedents and postcedents in terms of binding.
[src:agreement-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] Almost any syntactic category can serve as the antecedent to a pro-form.
[src:agreement-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] The following examples illustrate a range of proforms and their antecedents.
[src:agreement-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] This list of proforms and the types of antecedents that they take is by no means exhaustive, but rather it is intended to merely deliver an impression of the breadth of expressions that can function as proforms and antecedents.
[src:agreement-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] While the stereotypical proform is a pronoun and the stereotypical antecedent a noun or noun phrase, these examples demonstrate that most any syntactic category can in fact serve as an antecedent to a proform, whereby the proforms themselves are a diverse bunch.
[src:agreement-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] The last two examples are particularly interesting, because they show that some proforms can even take discontinuous word combinations as antecedents, i.e. the antecedents are *not* constituents.
[src:agreement-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] A particularly frequent type of proform occurs in relative clauses.
[src:agreement-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] Many relative clauses contain a relative pronoun, and these relative pronouns have an antecedent.
[src:agreement-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] Sentences 'd' and 'h' above contain relative clauses; the proforms *when* and *which* are relative proforms.
[src:agreement-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] In some cases, the wording could have an uncertain antecedent, where the antecedent of a pronoun is not clear because two or more prior nouns or phrases could match the count, gender, or logic as a prior reference.
[src:agreement-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] In such cases, scholars have recommended to rewrite the sentence structure to be more specific, or repeat the words of the antecedent rather than use only a pronoun phrase, as a technique to resolve the uncertain antecedent.
[src:agreement-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] For example, consider the sentence, "There was a doll inside the box that was made of clay", where the word "that" could refer to either the box or the doll.
[src:agreement-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] Antecedents may also be unclear when they occur far from the noun or phrase they refer to.
[src:agreement-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] Tyler, “War Imminent as Hussein Rejects Ultimatum,” N.Y.
[src:agreement-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] As Garner points out, “that were…the border” modifies “messages”, which occurs 7 words (3 of which are nouns) before.
[src:agreement-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] In context, the phrase could also modify “the Iraqi people”, hence the uncertainty.
[src:agreement-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] The *ante-* in *antecedent* means 'before; in front of'.
[src:agreement-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] Thus, when a pro-form precedes its antecedent, the antecedent is not literally an **ante**cedent, but rather it is a **post**cedent, *post-* meaning 'after; behind'.
[src:agreement-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] Postcedents are rare compared to antecedents, and in practice, the distinction between antecedents and postcedents is often ignored, with the term *antecedent* being used to denote both.
[src:agreement-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] This practice is a source of confusion, and some have therefore denounced using the term *antecedent* to mean *postcedent* because of this confusion.
[src:agreement-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] Some pro-forms lack a linguistic antecedent.
[src:agreement-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] In such cases, the antecedent is implied in the given discourse environment or from general knowledge of the world.
[src:agreement-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] For instance, the first person pronouns *I*, *me*, *we*, and *us* and the second person pronoun *you* are pro-forms that usually lack a linguistic antecedent.
[src:agreement-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] However, their antecedents are present in the discourse context as the speaker and the listener.
[src:agreement-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] Pleonastic pro-forms also lack a linguistic antecedent, e.g.
[src:agreement-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] *It is raining*, where the pronoun *it* is semantically empty and cannot be viewed as referring to anything specific in the discourse world.
[src:agreement-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] Definite pro-forms such as *they* and *you* also have an indefinite use, which means they denote some person or people in general, e.g.
[src:agreement-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] *They will get you for that*, and therefore cannot be construed as taking a linguistic antecedent.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p01] Weakness is an inherent property of a given verb determined by the particular consonants of the verb root (corresponding to a verb conjugation in Classical Latin and other European languages), with five main types of weakness and two or three subtypes of each type.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p01] Arabic grammarians typically use the root ف-ع-ل **f-ʿ-l** to indicate the particular shape of any given element of a verbal paradigm.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p01] As an example, the form يتكاتب (root: ك-ت-ب) **yutakātabu** 'he is corresponded (with)' would be listed generically as يتفاعل **yutafāʿalu** (yuta1ā2a3u), specifying the generic shape of a strong Form VI passive verb, third-person masculine singular present indicative.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p01] Each of these has its own stem form, and each of these stem forms itself comes in numerous varieties, according to the weakness (or lack thereof) of the underlying root.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p01] Each particular lexical verb is specified by four stems, two each for the active and passive voices.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p01] In a particular voice, one stem (the *perfective stem*) is usually used for the past tense, and the other (the *imperfective stem*) is usually used for the present and future tenses, along with non-indicative moods, e.g. subjunctive and imperative.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p01] Though there is still some disagreement about the interpretation of the stems as tense or aspect, the dominant current view is that the stems represent aspect, sometimes of a relative rather than absolute nature.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p01] To the past stem, suffixes are added to mark the verb for person, number and gender, while to the non-past stem, a combination of prefixes and suffixes are added.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p01] (Very approximately, the prefixes specify the person and the suffixes indicate number and gender.) A total of 13 forms exist for each of the two stems, specifying person (first, second or third); number (singular, dual or plural); and gender (masculine or feminine).
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p01] There are six separate moods in the non-past: indicative, imperative, subjunctive, jussive, short energetic and long energetic.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p01] The moods are generally marked by suffixes.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p01] When no number suffix is present, the endings are **-u** for indicative, **-a** for subjunctive, no ending for imperative and jussive, ـَنْ **-an** for shorter energetic, ـَنَّ **-anna** for longer energetic.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p01] When number suffixes are present, the moods are either distinguished by different forms of the suffixes (e.g. ـُونَ **-ūna** for masculine plural indicative vs. ـُو **-ū** for masculine plural subjunctive/imperative/jussive), or not distinguished at all.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p01] The imperative exists only in the second person and is distinguished from the jussive by the lack of the normal second-person prefix ـت **ta-/tu-**.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p01] The third person masculine singular past tense form serves as the "dictionary form" used to identify a verb, similar to the infinitive in English.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p01] (Arabic has no infinitive.) For example, the verb meaning 'write' is often specified as كَتَبَ **kataba**, which actually means 'he wrote'.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p01] This indicates that the past-tense stem is كَتَبْـ **katab-**; the corresponding non-past stem is ـكْتُبْـ **-ktub-**, as in يَكْتُبُ **yaktubu** 'he writes'.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p01] Using the third person masculine singular as the dictionary citation form is more useful in that the vowels that appear in the remaining present tense forms are evident.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p01] Especially in form I verbs, without prior knowledge, these vowels are often not evident based purely on the past-tense forms.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p01] There are three tenses in Arabic: the past tense (اَلْمَاضِي **al-māḍī**), the present tense (اَلْمُضَارِع **al-muḍāriʿ**) and the future tense.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p01] The future tense in Classical Arabic is formed by adding either the prefix ‏سَـ‎ **sa-** or the separate word ‏سَوْفَ‎ **sawfa** onto the beginning of the present tense verb, e.g. سَيَكْتُبُ *sa-yaktubu* or سَوْفَ يَكْتُبُ *sawfa yaktubu* 'he will write'.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p01] In some contexts, the tenses represent aspectual distinctions rather than tense distinctions.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p01] In all but Form I, there is only one possible shape for each of the past and non-past stems for a given root.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p01] In Form I, however, different verbs have different shapes.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p01] Notice that the second vowel can be any of **a i u** in both past and non-past stems.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p01] The vowel **a** occurs in most past stems, while **i** occurs in some (especially intransitive) and **u** occurs only in a few stative verbs (i.e. whose meaning is 'be X' or 'become X' where X is an adjective).
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p01] In less formal Arabic and in spoken dialects, the subjunctive mood is used as the only imperfective tense (subjunctivism) and the final ḥarakah vowel is not pronounced.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p01] The imperative (صِيغَة اَلْأَمْر **ṣīghat al-amr**) (positive, only 2nd person) is formed by dropping the verbal prefix (ت-) from the imperfective jussive stem, e.g. قَدِّم **qaddim** 'present!'.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p01] Negative imperatives are formed from the jussive.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p01] The exception to the above rule is the form (or stem) IV verbs.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p01] In these verbs a non-elidible alif ا pronounced as **a-** is always prefixed to the imperfect jussive form, e.g. أَرْسِلْ **arsil** "send!", أَضِفْ **aḍif** 'add!'.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p01] The subjunctive is used in subordinate clauses after certain conjunctions.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p01] The jussive is used in negation, in negative imperatives, and in the hortative **la**+jussive.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p01] Arabic has two verbal voices (صِيغَات **ṣīghāt** "forms", sg. صِيغَة **ṣīghah**), active (صِيغَة اَلْمَعْلُوم **ṣīghat al-maʿlūm**), and passive (صِيغَة اَلْمَجْهُول **ṣīghat al-majhūl**).
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p01] The passive voice is expressed by a change in vocalization.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p01] Thus, the active and passive forms are spelled identically in Arabic; only their vowel markings differ.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p01] There are some exceptions to this in the case of weak roots.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p01] Every verb has a corresponding active participle, and most have passive participles.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p01] E.g. معلم **muʿallim** 'teacher' is the active participle to stem II. of the root ع-ل-م **ʿ-l-m** ('know').
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p01] In addition to a participle, there is a verbal noun (in Arabic, مَصْدَر **maṣdar**, pl. مَصَادِر **maṣādir**, literally meaning 'source'), sometimes called a gerund, which is similar to English gerunds and verb-derived nouns of various sorts (e.g.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p01] "running" and "a run" from "to run"; "objection" from "to object").
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p01] As shown by the English examples, its meaning refers both to the act of doing something and (by frequent semantic extension) to its result.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p01] One of its syntactic functions is as a verbal complement of another verb, and this usage it corresponds to the English gerund or infinitive (*He prevented me from **running*** or *He began **to run***).
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p01] Some well-known examples of verbal nouns are فتح **fatḥ** (see Fatah) (Form I), تنظيم **tanẓīm** (Form II), جهاد **jihād** (Form III), إسلام **islām** (Form IV), انتفاضة **intifāḍah** (feminine of Form VIII verbal noun), and استقلال **istiqlāl** (Form X).
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p01] The system of verb conjugations in Arabic is quite complicated, and is formed along two axes.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p01] One axis, known as the *form* (described as "Form I", "Form II", etc.), is used to specify grammatical concepts such as causative, intensive, reciprocal, passive or reflexive, and involves varying the stem form.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p01] The other axis, known as the *weakness*, is determined by the particular consonants making up the root.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p01] For example, *defective* (or *third-weak* or final-weak) verbs have a و **w** or ي **y** as the last root consonant (e.g. ر-م-ي **r-m-y** 'throw', د-ع-و **d-ʿ-w** 'call'), and *doubled* (or geminated) verbs have the second and third consonants the same (e.g. م-د-د **m-d-d** 'extend').
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p01] These "weaknesses" have the effect of inducing various irregularities in the stems and endings of the associated verbs.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] In Arabic the grammatical person and number as well as the mood are designated by a variety of prefixes and suffixes.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] The following table shows the paradigm of a regular sound Form I verb, **kataba** (كتب) 'to write'.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] Most of the final short vowels are often omitted in speech, except the vowel of the feminine plural ending **-na**, and normally the vowel of the past tense second person feminine singular ending **-ti**.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] In unvocalised Arabic, **katabtu**, **katabta**, **katabti** and **katabat** are all written the same: كتبت.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] Forms **katabtu** and **katabta** (and sometimes even **katabti**) can be abbreviated to **katabt** in spoken Arabic and in pausa, making them also sound the same.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] ا (*alif*) in final ـُوا (*-ū*) is silent.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] Roots containing one or two of the radicals و **w** (**wāw**), ي **y** (**yāʾ** ) or ء **ʾ** (**hamzah**) often lead to verbs with special phonological rules because these radicals can be influenced by their surroundings.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] Such verbs are called "weak" (*verba infirma*, 'weak verbs') and their paradigms must be given special attention.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] According to the position of the weak radical in the root, the root can be classified into four classes: *first weak*, *second weak*, *third weak* (or final weak) and *doubled*, where both the second and third radicals are identical.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] Some roots fall into more than one category at once.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] Most first-weak verbs have a و *w* or ي *y* as their first radical.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] These verbs are entirely regular in the past tense.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] In the non-past, the *w* drops out if non-past uses kasra, leading to a shorter stem (e.g., (يَجِدُ) وَجَدَ *wajada (yajidu)* 'to find'), where the stem is ـجِدـ *-jid-* in place of a longer stem like ـجْلِدـ *-jlid-* from the verb جَلَدَ (يَجْلِدُ) *jalada (yajlidu)* 'to whip, flog'.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] This same stem is used throughout, and there are no other irregularities except for the imperative, which has no initial vowel, consistent with the fact that the stem for the imperative begins with only one consonant.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] If non-past employs damma, then it doesn't drop.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] If non-past uses fatha, it most often drops out but in some verbs it stays.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] It also doesn't drop out if the verb is also doubled.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] The following shows a paradigm of a typical Form I hollow (second-weak) verb قَالَ (قُلْتُ، يَقُولُ) *qāla (qultu, yaqūlu)* (root: ق-و-ل *q-w-l*) 'to say', parallel to verbs of the فَعَلَ (يَفْعُلُ) *faʿala (yafʿulu)* type.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] See notes following the table for explanation.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] All hollow (second-weak) verbs are conjugated in a parallel fashion.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] The endings are identical to those of strong verbs, but there are two stems (a longer and a shorter) in each of the past and non-past.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] The longer stem is consistently used whenever the ending begins with a vowel, and the shorter stem is used in all other circumstances.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] The longer stems end in a long vowel plus consonant, while the shorter stems end in a short vowel plus consonant.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] The shorter stem is formed simply by shortening the vowel of the long stem in *all paradigms other than the active past of Form I verbs*.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] In the active past paradigms of Form I, however, the longer stem always has an *ā* vowel, while the shorter stem has a vowel *u* or *i* corresponding to the actual second root consonant of the verb.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] No initial vowel is needed in the imperative forms because the non-past stem does not begin with two consonants.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] There are rare cases where Form I hollow verbs are conjugated as regular verbs because their second radical employs kasra, cancelling the long vowel formation.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] Their passives, if artificially derived at all, would also be regular, using ـُوِـ **-uwi-** or ـُيِـ **-uyi-** instead of ـِيـ **-ī-** in past and ـْوَـ **-wa-** or ـْيَـ **-ya-** instead of ـَاـ **-ā-** in non-past, without transforming the weak radical into the long vowels.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] The following shows a paradigm of a typical Form I defective (third-weak) verb رَمَى (يَرْمِي) *ramā (yarmī)* (root: ر-م-ي *r-m-y*) 'to throw', parallel to verbs of the فَعَلَ (يَفْعِلُ) *faʿala (yafʿilu)* type.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] Each of the two main stems (past and non-past) comes in two variants, a full and a shortened.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] For the past stem, the full is رَمَيـ *ramay-*, shortened to رَمـ *ram-* in much of the third person (i.e. before vowels, in most cases).
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] For the non-past stem, the full is *rmiy-*, shortened to *rm-* before *-ū -ī*.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] The full non-past stem رْمِيْـ *rmiy-* appears as رْمِيـ *rmī-* when not before a vowel; this is an automatic alternation in Classical Arabic.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] The places where the shortened stems occur are indicated by silver (past), gold (non-past).
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] The endings are actually mostly regular.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] The following shows a paradigm of a typical Form I defective (third-weak) verb دَعَا (يَدْعُو) (root: د-ع-و) *daʿā (yadʿū)* 'to call', parallel to verbs of the فَعَلَ (يَفْعُلُ) *faʿala (yafʿulu)* type.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] Verbs of this sort are entirely parallel to verbs of the فَعَا (يَفْعِي) *faʿā (yafʿī)* type, although the exact forms can still be tricky.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] Verbs of this sort are work nearly identically to verbs of the فَعَى (يَفْعِي) *faʿā (yafʿī)* type.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] The following shows a paradigm of a typical Form I defective (third-weak) verb نَسِيَ (يَنْسَ) *nasiya (yansā)* (root: ن-س-ي) 'to forget', parallel to verbs of the فَعِلَ (يَفْعَلُ) *faʿila (yafʿalu)* type.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] These verbs differ in a number of significant respects from either of the above types.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] This variant is somewhat different from the variants with ـِي *-ī* or ـُو *-ū* in the non-past.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] As with other third-weak verbs, there are multiple stems in each of the past and non-past, a full stem composed following the normal rules and one or more shortened stems.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] The modified stem ـنْسَى *-nsā* occurs in "endingless" forms (i.e. masculine or common-gender singular, plus 1st plural).
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] As usual with third-weak verbs, it is shortened to ـنْسَ *-nsa* in the jussive.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] The table above chooses to segment them as تَنْسَيْنَ *ta-nsa-yna*, تَنْسَوْنَ *ta-nsa-wna*, suggesting that a shortened stem ـنْسَـ *-nsa-* combines with irregular (compressed) endings ـيْنَ *-yna* < *ـِينَ **-īna*, ـوْنَ *-wna* < ـُونَ **-ūna*.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] Similarly subjunctive/jussive تَسنَوْا *ta-nsaw* < تَسنَيُوْا **ta-nsay-ū*; but note energetic تَنْسَوُنَّ *ta-nsawunna* < تَنْسَيُنَّ **ta-nsay-unna*, where the original ـيُـ **-yu-* has assimilated to ـوُـ *-wu-*.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] Consistent with the above analysis, we analyze this form as تَنْسَوُنَّ *ta-nsa-wunna*, with an irregular energetic ending ـوُنَّ *-wunna* where a glide consonant has developed after the previous vowel.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] However, since all moods in this case have a form containing ـنْسَوـ *-nsaw-*, an alternative analysis would consider ـنْسَوـ *-nsaw* and ـنْسَيـ *-nsay* as stems.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] Verbs of this sort are nearly identical to verbs of the فَعِيَ (يَفْعَى) *faʿiya (yafʿā)* type in past (except employing a different corresponding long vowel) and identical to verbs of the فَعَا (يَفْعُو) *faʿā (yafʿū)* type in non-past/imperative.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] Those verbs are parallel to verbs of the فَعَلَ (يَفْعَلُ) *faʿala (yafʿalu)*.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] Verbs of this sort are identical to verbs of the فَعَى (يَفْعِي) *faʿā (yafʿī)* type in past and فَعِيَ (يَفْعَى) *faʿiya (yafʿā)* in non-past/imperative.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] The following shows a paradigm of a typical Form I doubled verb مَدَّ (يَمُدُّ) (root: م-د-د) *madda (yamuddu)* 'to extend', parallel to verbs of the فَعَلَ (يَفْعُلُ) *faʿala (yafʿulu)* type.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] All doubled verbs are conjugated in a parallel fashion.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] The endings are for the most part identical to those of strong verbs, but there are two stems (a regular and a modified) in each of the past and non-past.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] The regular stems are identical to the stem forms of sound verbs, while the modified stems have the two identical consonants pulled together into a geminate consonant and the vowel between moved before the geminate.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] In the above verb مَدَّ (يَمُدُّ) *madda (yamuddu)* 'to extend (s.th.)', the past stems are مَدَدـ *madad-* (regular), مَدّـ *madd-* (modified), and the non-past stems are مْدُدـ *mdud-* (regular), مُدّـ *mudd-* (modified).
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] In the table, places where the regular past stem occurs are in silver, and places where the regular non-past stem occurs are in gold; everywhere else, the modified stem occurs.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] No initial vowel is needed in most of the imperative forms because the modified non-past stem does not begin with two consonants.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] The concept of having two stems for each tense, one for endings beginning with vowels and one for other endings, occurs throughout the different kinds of weaknesses.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] Following the above rules, endingless jussives would have a form like تَمْدُد *tamdud*, while the corresponding indicatives and subjunctives would have forms like تَمُدُّ *tamuddu*, تَمُدَّ *tamudda*.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] As a result, for the doubled verbs in particular, there is a tendency to harmonize these forms by adding a vowel to the jussives, usually ـَ *a*, sometimes ـِ *i*.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] These are the only irregular endings in these paradigms, and have been indicated in boldface.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p02] The masculine singular imperative likewise has multiple forms, based on the multiple forms of the jussive.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] Arabic verb morphology includes **augmentations** of the root, also known as **forms**, an example of the derived stems found among the Semitic languages.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] For a typical verb based on a triliteral root (i.e. a root formed using three root consonants), the basic form is termed **Form I**, while the augmented forms are known as **Form II**, **Form III**, etc.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] The forms in normal use are Form I through Form X; Forms XI through XV exist but are rare and obsolescent.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] Forms IX and XI are used only with adjectival roots referring to colors and physical defects (e.g.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] "red", "blue", "blind", "deaf", etc.), and are stative verbs having the meaning of "be X" or "become X" (e.g.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] Form IX **iḥmarra** 'be red, become red, blush', Form XI **iḥmārra** with the same meaning).
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] Although the *structure* that a given root assumes in a particular augmentation is predictable, its *meaning* is not (although many augmentations have one or more "usual" or prototypical meanings associated with them), and not all augmentations exist for any given root.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] As a result, these augmentations are part of the system of derivational morphology, not part of the inflectional system.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] The construction of a given augmentation is normally indicated using the dummy root *f–ʿ–l* (ف–ع–ل), based on the verb **faʿala** 'to do'.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] Because Arabic has no direct equivalent to the infinitive form of Western languages, the third-person masculine singular past tense is normally used as the *dictionary form* of a given verb, i.e. the form by which a verb is identified in a dictionary or grammatical discussion.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] Hence, the word **faʿala** above actually has the meaning of 'he did', but is translated as 'to do' when used as a dictionary form.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] Verbs based on quadriliteral roots (roots with four consonants) also exist.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] There are four augmentations for such verbs, known as Forms Iq, IIq, IIIq and IVq.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] These have forms similar to Forms II, V, VII and IX respectively of triliteral verbs.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] The construction of such verbs is typically given using the dummy verb **faʿlala** (root: ف-ع-ل-ل).
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] However, the choice of this particular verb is somewhat non-ideal in that the third and fourth consonants of an actual verb are typically not the same, despite the same consonant used for both; this is a particular problem e.g. for Form IVq.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] The verb tables below use the dummy verb **faʿlaqa** (root: ف-ع-ل-ق) instead.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] Some grammars, especially of colloquial spoken varieties rather than of Classical Arabic, use other dummy roots.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] For example, *A Short Reference Grammar of Iraqi Arabic* (Wallace M.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] Erwin) uses فمل **FaMaLa** (root: ف-م-ل) and فستل **FaSTaLa** (root: ف-س-ت-ل) for three and four-character roots, respectively (standing for "First Middle Last" and "First Second Third Last").
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] Commonly the dummy consonants are given in capital letters.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] The system of identifying verb augmentations by Roman numerals is an invention by Western scholars.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] Traditionally, Arabic grammarians did not number the augmentations at all, instead identifying them by the corresponding dictionary form.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] For example, Form V would be called "the **tafaʿʿala** form".
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] which is often "with" and sometimes "against".
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] ("be X", "become X"), specially for colors (e.g.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] Each form can have either active or passive forms in the past and non-past tenses, so reflexives are different from passives.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] Note that the present passive of forms I and IV are the same.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] Some verbs that would be classified as "weak" according to the consonants of the verb root are nevertheless conjugated as a strong verb.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] Form VIII has a ـتـ -*t*- that is infixed into the root, directly after the first root consonant.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] This ـتـ -*t*- assimilates to certain coronal consonants occurring as the first root consonant.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] In particular, with roots whose first consonant is د، ز، ث، ذ، ص، ط، ض، ظ *d z th dh ṣ ṭ ḍ ẓ*, the combination of root and infix ت *t* appears as دّ، زد، ثّ، ذّ، صط، طّ، ضط، ظّ *dd zd thth dhdh ṣṭ ṭṭ ḍṭ ẓẓ*.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] That is, the *t* assimilates the emphasis of the emphatic consonants ص، ط، ض، ظ *ṣ ṭ ḍ ẓ* and the voicing of د، ز *d z*, and assimilates entirely to the interdental consonants ث، ذ، ظ *th dh ẓ*.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] Other than for Form I active, there is only one possible form for each verb, regardless of whether the third root consonant is و **w** or ي **y**.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] All of the derived third-weak verbs have the same active-voice endings as (فعى (يفعي **faʿā (yafʿī)** verbs except for Forms V and VI, which have past-tense endings like (فعى (يفعي **faʿā (yafʿī)** verbs but non-past endings like (فعي (يفعى **faʿiya (yafʿā)** verbs.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] The passive-voice endings of all third-weak verbs (whether Form I or derived) are the same as for the (فعي (يفعى **faʿiya (yafʿā)** verbs.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] The verbal nouns have various irregularities: feminine in Form II, *-in* declension in Form V and VI, glottal stop in place of root *w/y* in Forms VII–X.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] The active and passive participles of derived defective verbs consistently are of the *-in* and *-an* declensions, respectively.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] Defective Form IX verbs are extremely rare.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] Heywood and Nahmad list one such verb, **iʿmāya** 'be/become blind', which does not follow the expected form اعميّ ***iʿmayya**.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] They also list a similarly rare Form XI verb اعمايّ **iʿmāyya** 'be/become blind' — this time with the expected form.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] Only the forms with irregularities are shown.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] The missing forms are entirely regular, with *w* or *y* appearing as the second radical, depending on the root.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] There are unexpected feminine forms of the verbal nouns of Form IV, X.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] When the first radical is *w*, it drops out in the Form I non-past.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] Most of the derived forms are regular, except that the sequences *uw iw* are assimilated to *ū ī*, and the sequence *wt* in Form VIII is assimilated to *tt* throughout the paradigm.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] The following table only shows forms with irregularities in them.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] The initial *w* also drops out in the common Form I verbal noun علة *ʿilah* (e.g. صلة *ṣilah* 'arrival, link' from وصلة *waṣalah* 'arrive').
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] When the first radical is *y*, the forms are largely regular.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] The following table only shows forms that have some irregularities in them, indicated in **boldface**.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] The largest problem with so-called "hamzated" verbs (those with a glottal stop *ʾ* or "hamzah" as any of the root consonants) is the complicated way of writing such verbs in the Arabic script (see the article on hamzah for the rules regarding this).
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] In pronunciation, these verbs are in fact almost entirely regular.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] The only irregularity occurs in verbs with a hamzah ء as the first radical.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] A phonological rule in Classical Arabic disallows the occurrence of two hamzahs in a row separated by a short vowel, assimilating the second to the preceding vowel (hence *ʾaʾ ʾiʾ ʾuʾ* become *ʾā ʾī ʾū*).
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] In addition, any place where a **hamzat al-waṣl** (elidable hamzah) occurs will *optionally* undergo this transformation.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] Doubly weak verbs have two "weak" radicals; a few verbs are also triply weak.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] Generally, the above rules for weak verbs apply in combination, as long as they do not conflict.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] The Classical Arabic system of verbs is largely unchanged in the colloquial spoken varieties of Arabic.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] The same derivational system of augmentations exists, including triliteral Forms I through X and quadriliteral Forms I and II, constructed largely in the same fashion (the rare triliteral Forms XI through XV and quadriliteral Forms III and IV have vanished).
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] The same system of weaknesses (strong, defective/third-weak, hollow/second-weak, assimilated/first-weak, doubled) also exists, again constructed largely in the same fashion.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] Within a given verb, two stems (past and non-past) still exist along with the same two systems of affixes (suffixing past-tense forms and prefixing/suffixing non-past forms).
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] The largest changes are within a given paradigm, with a significant reduction in the number of forms.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] The following is an example of a regular verb paradigm in Egyptian Arabic.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] In addition, Form IV is lost entirely in most varieties, except for a few "classicizing" verbs (i.e. verbs borrowed from Modern Standard Arabic).
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] See varieties of Arabic for more information on grammar differences in the spoken varieties.
[src:agreement-linguistics/arabic-verbs-p03] The negation of Arabic verbs varies according to the tense of the verb phrase.
